  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States\n- Initial focus on financial reporting and record-keeping\n- Limited scope of regulation\n\n2. International Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed comprehensive international standards\n- Created global recommendations for anti-money laundering (AML) practices\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Expanded financial institution obligations\n- Strengthened cross-border information sharing\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Increased regulations targeting digital currencies\n- Enhanced due diligence for online financial transactions\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced beneficial ownership transparency\n- More sophisticated risk-based approaches\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Emerging Focus Areas\n- Cybercrime prevention\n- Terrorist financing detection\n- Complex transaction monitoring\n- Machine learning and AI integration in compliance\n\nThese developments represent a comprehensive, dynamic approach to combating financial crimes.",
